I’ve been trying to tune my teams swerve drive gains using Sysid. I am using the generated routines that are provided by CTRE Swerve generator. When I load the logs into Sysid, using one of the drive motors Position, Velocity, and MotorVoltage, with units of Rotations, I recieve an error that Quasistatic Test trimming removed all data or that there is too little acceleration data. Moreover in the Quasistatic Velocity vs Time graph it shows only a few 0 m/s data points.

I opened the log in AdvantageScope to see if for some reason Quasistatic Velocity wasn’t being recorded, but as far as I could tell everything looks right.

The Errors

Screenshot 2025-02-18 at 11.17.35 PM962×202 49.3 KB

AScope Graph

Screenshot 2025-02-18 at 11.03.05 PM1456×644 38.5 KB

Yellow is Position, Red is Velocity, Purple is Voltage.

From the graph in AS the velocity vs time during the quasistatic tests is linear which I would expect, and the velocity during the dynamic tests is vaguely exponential (though maybe not smooth enough?), which I would also expect.

  1. If anyone has any ideas about what I might be doing wrong with SysId it would incredibly helpful.

  2. In the meantime, I’ve tried analyzing the logs by hand. My understanding is the during the quasistatic test I can ballpark kV as the slope of velocity vs time as the acceleration is comparatively little so kA*a is also ~ 0? Then, during the dynamic test, because acceleration is so high for the first part, can I ballpark kA as the (slope of dynamic velocity vs time during the acceleration period) / voltage? I’m not planning on using kS but if I did it would just be the y-intercept of the quasistatic velocity vs time graph right?

  3. I’m mostly interested in estimating MOI using SysId. If the previous method gives kA_linear how can I go about finding kA_Angular?
    Pathplanner provides the formula I = mass * trackwidth / 2 * kA_Angular / kA_linear, where I is in kgM^2. I can’t seem to reconcile how these units work out, so any insight would be appreciated.

Sorry about the long and rambling post, and thank you very much for any help!
